        "screen_content": "Assessment ensures the equipment fits real-world needs. We look at three intersecting factors—using plain language rather than clinical model names: THE PERSON — What can they do right now? What are their goals? What are their cognitive and physical limits? THE ENVIRONMENT — Where will this equipment be used? What physical features help or hinder? What supports exist in the home and community? THE ACTIVITY — What specific task are we supporting? Showering? Getting to the toilet at night? Walking to the letterbox? Accordion panels: Panel 1 (The Person): Includes functional status, prognosis trajectory (improving post-op vs declining/palliative), cognition, health literacy, psychosocial readiness, carer availability. Panel 2 (The Environment): Includes home layout, bathroom configuration, doorway widths, steps, lighting, floor surfaces, transport/car boot size, rural/remote access constraints. Panel 3 (The Activity): Includes the specific occupation or task being addressed, frequency, independence requirements, safety margin needed. These three factors overlap—and it is in the overlap that safe prescription decisions are made.",
